In this update:
[1] Pakistan - EpiCore Surveillance Project follow-up to request for information (RFI)
[2] Nigeria - Bauchi, positive environmental samples cVDPV2

******
[1] Pakistan - EpiCore Surveillance Project follow-up to RFI
Date: Fri 19 Oct 2018
From: EpiCore Surveillance Project [edited]


An EpiCore Surveillance project member provided the following information on the "atypical" clinical presentation and vaccination history of the newly confirmed wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1)-associated disease in the Gadap area of Karachi, in Sindh province. The case involved a 42-month-old female with date of onset of disease on 22 Sep 2018. The child had a verbal history of 3 doses of oral polio vaccine (OPV) and no doses of inactivated polio vaccine (IPV) as part of routine immunization activities, although this was not verified by review of a vaccination card. The child also received more than 7 doses of OPV during supplementary immunization activities.

Clinically, the child was well until falling down, after which she began to have pain in her right hip and weakness of bilateral lower extremities. An X-ray revealed a dislocation of the right hip joint.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Surveillance Project

[ProMED-mail would like to thank the EpiCore Surveillance Project members for assisting in clarifying the information (or lack of information) on this event occurring in Sindh province.

When reading the details of the clinical presentation, I am reminded of doing active surveillance for polio cases in northeastern states of Brazil, back in the early days of launching the polio-eradication effort in the Americas. We found one case that, after sustaining a fall, had been admitted and discharged from the hospital without any fractures and was discharged with a diagnosis of trauma. The lesson learned was this: during known or suspected poliovirus transmission in a geographic area (defined widely), and with a history of trauma with noticeable post-trauma acute flaccid paralysis (AFP), think polio and obtain specimens. The fall may have been a result of the AFP, rather than the cause of the AFP. Fortunately, in this instance in Pakistan, an astute healthcare worker in the "stop polio program" did obtain specimens, and poliovirus infection was confirmed. As for the history of multiple doses of OPV, unfortunately, there are instances of vaccine failures: sometimes it is failure to get the vaccine, while at other times, other competing events interfere with the vaccine viruses attaching to their receptor sites in the individual, with the verdict on the multifactoral etiologies still pending.

In Newell E et al (see ref. below), researchers postulated that tropical enteropathy and resultant inflammation from endotoxin exposure might be one etiology for the reduced immune response to multiple doses of OPV. They found that children with vaccine failure demonstrated a reduced cellular responsiveness to cytokine stimulations and elevated pro-inflammatory cytokine expression. They concluded that OPV failure (and other orally administered vaccines) was related to malnutrition, gut barrier dysfunction, and a shorter length of breastfeeding in early childhood and is associated with a chronic inflammatory immune phenotype (Newell E, Sigal N, Haque R, Kidd B, Tse T, Petri W, Davis M: Oral polio vaccination failure in urban slum children is associated with malnutrition and evidence of chronic inflammation. J Immunol. May 1, 2012; 188(1 Supplement): 166.2. http://www.jimmunol.org/content/188/1_Supplement/166.2).

So the final pending question on this case is whether there is residual paralysis at the end of the recommended 60-day observation period, or whether the identification of transient paralytic disease associated with isolation of the WPV would remain classified as a case of polio this year, as this "case" is very relevant to activities related to polio eradication efforts and outcomes.

Note we are still waiting for additional information on the other case confirmed in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. - Mod.MPP

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map:
Sindh, Pakistan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6102512,63829]

